        "num_reports": 0,
        "comments": [
            {
                "comment_id": 1,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 1,
                "content": "As a first-time buyer saving for a small apartment, this update makes me a bit nervous. Does the 8% QoQ dip in prime spill over into more affordable areas (JVC, IMPZ, Town Square), or is it mostly affecting high-end? With DLD volumes down 22%, are sellers more open to negotiation now, or are listings just pulling back? \n\nAre banks tightening mortgage approvals because of this \"risk-off\" mood? I\u2019m debating whether to lock a fixed rate now or wait 3\u20136 months. Any data on mid-market prices vs rents in Q1 would really help. I don\u2019t want to catch a falling knife, but I\u2019m also worried rents will keep climbing. \n\nFor first-time buyers, what should we be watching most right now\u2014service charges, developer incentives/payment plans, or off-plan risks? Would appreciate insights from agents/analysts.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:43:41.718380",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 2,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 14,
                "content": "Looks like a healthy breather, not a meltdown. I bought a 2BR in Dubai Marina in 2019 and I\u2019m selling now at ~+40%. Good stock is still getting multiple viewings and sensible offers. QoQ \u201cprime\u201d can be super lumpy (seasonality + global jitters), but end-user demand and quality rentals are holding up. If you\u2019re staying long-term: buy quality, great location, solid developer, realistic service charges. Don\u2019t expect 2021\u201323 rocket ships, but A-grade units will be fine. I\u2019m heading back to the UK so I\u2019m cashing out, but if I were staying I\u2019d still be adding in Marina/Downtown/Palm. Doomers shout \u2018top\u2019 every quarter \u2014 it\u2019s usually just a wobble. #DubaiRealEstate",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:46:23.591780",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 3,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 7,
                "content": "Healthy breather, not a breakdown. After record prints, a 20\u201325% volume normalization is textbook in a maturing market. Fundamentals haven\u2019t changed: net migration and company formation (helped by Golden Visas), strong end-user demand, tight rentals, and Vision 2040 driving infrastructure and jobs. \n\nFor end-users and long-term investors, an 8% QoQ dip is a window to lock quality assets\u2014focus on community, build quality, service charges, and cashflow. On our side at Creek Harbour and Dubai Hills, construction is on schedule; we\u2019re rolling out flexible and post-handover plans to de-risk entry. Cycles breathe\u2014opportunity favors the prepared.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:46:30.152960",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 4,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 9,
                "content": "Seen this movie before. QoQ dips after a hot run aren\u2019t a \u201cdownturn\u201d by default. Ramadan/Eid always slow viewings and transfers. Prime sales price \u2260 rental reality \u2014 Marina and JVC viewings are still busy, yields are holding, and collections are >98% on time for me.\n\nSupply coming online is mostly peripheral; true prime stock is tight. Tenants expecting 2020 rents will be disappointed. Renewals are being adjusted within RERA guidelines where units are below market \u2014 that won\u2019t change because of one soft quarter.\n\nHealthy breather > bubble. Watch the next 2 quarters: net migration, new Ejari registrations, vacancy in established towers. If those stay firm, this is consolidation, not a slide. I\u2019m holding my line on rents.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:46:56.802260",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 5,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 10,
                "content": "A cooling in the prime segment doesn\u2019t automatically translate into affordability for ordinary residents. If anything, volume dips can push developers to pause mid-income projects first. This is a window to rebalance supply toward end\u2011users: accelerate approvals for affordable rentals, set inclusionary requirements in large masterplans, release public land for social housing, and incentivize smaller, transit\u2011linked units over trophy assets. Also strengthen tenant protections with predictable rent index updates and discourage land banking.\n\nDubai\u2019s structural demand is still strong (population, jobs, infrastructure), so a sharp downturn isn\u2019t inevitable. It\u2019s a healthy correction only if it reduces speculation and redirects capital to livable, mixed-income communities. Would love to see DLD publish more granular data on prime vs mid-market absorption, vacancy, and rental stress to guide policy. Luxury has its place\u2014but it shouldn\u2019t dominate the pipeline.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:48:10.396400",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 6,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 6,
                "content": "33F Indian expat, renting in Dubai for 6 years and on the fence about buying. This update gives me mixed feelings: relief that prices are cooling, but also anxiety\u2014am I about to catch a falling knife or miss the bottom if things bounce?\n\nA few questions for folks closer to the data:\n- Is the 8% QoQ dip mainly in prime (Palm/DIFC/Downtown) or are mid-market areas like JVC, Arjan, Dubai Hills mid-tier, Discovery Gardens, etc., also softening?\n- Are sellers actually negotiating 5\u201310% now, or still sticky on asking?\n- DLD volume down 22%\u2014how much of that is Ramadan/Eid seasonality vs genuine demand thinning?\n- Any signs of rents easing yet, or still climbing? My renewal is in June and that timing is stressing me out.\n- For end-use 1\u20132BR buyers with mortgages, is it smarter to wait a quarter or two for clarity, or do Dubai corrections typically move fast and then bounce?\n- Off-plan vs ready: are payment plans getting sweeter, or are developers holding firm?\n\nIf anyone can share recent comps, price/sqft trends, DOM, average price reductions, or yield math post-fees, I\u2019d be super grateful. I\u2019ve got cold feet but major FOMO whenever prices run. Also trying to factor in the whole visa-dependency risk\u2014don\u2019t want to be over-leveraged. Any pragmatic frameworks to decide would help.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:50:38.067500",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 7,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 13,
                "content": "As a British-Pakistani expat who just moved from London and is weighing a purchase here, this makes me pause. A few questions for the data-minded folks:\n\n- When you say \u201cprime\u201d down 8% QoQ, what\u2019s the exact basket (Palm, Downtown, DIFC, JBR?), and how does this compare with mid-market/freehold communities (JVC, Dubai Hills, MBR City, Dubailand, etc.)?\n- The 22% drop in DLD transaction volumes: is that heavier in off-plan reservations or secondary transfers? Any read on cash vs. mortgage buyer split?\n- Mortgage environment for expats: are banks tightening LTVs/DSR or repricing? Any differences for UAE-salaried residents vs non-residents?\n- Currency angle: for GBP-based buyers, how do AED price moves translate in GBP terms this quarter? Anyone crunched the FX-adjusted figures?\n- Developer incentives: are we seeing DLD fee waivers, post-handover payment plans, or furnished offers creeping back like in 2020\u201321?\n- Rentals: are rents flattening in prime while yields compress, or still rising? Any evidence of rising vacancy/longer days-to-lease?\n- Supply pipeline: how much inventory is due 2025\u201327 in prime cores vs outer communities? Any recommended dashboards (DLD, Cavendish Maxwell, CBRE, JLL, Knight Frank)?\n- Risk/ protections: for off-plan, how robust are escrow/milestone safeguards in practice? Any recent enforcement cases or buyer recourse examples? (Trying to benchmark vs. UK legal protections.)\n- Early stress indicators: longer DOM, price cuts >10%, cancelled cheques, or developer resales at discounts?\n\nIf anyone has links to the underlying DLD data or quarterly reports, please share. Trying to decide whether to proceed now or wait for more clarity.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:51:04.220660",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 8,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 3,
                "content": "As someone who has worked through two Dubai cycles, a few quick thoughts:\n\n- Prime is the most volatile slice; an 8% QoQ move can happen without implying a broad crash. Check YoY and segment-level data before drawing conclusions.\n- Volumes -22% can reflect seasonality (Ramadan/Eid) and buyers pausing for price discovery, not necessarily distress.\n- What I\u2019m watching: days-on-market, % of listings with price cuts, active inventory trend, developer incentives, and off-plan absorption/cancellation rates.\n- Opportunities: mid-prime with strong tenant demand and sensible service charges; motivated sellers on over-ambitious ask prices where pre-approved buyers can negotiate.\n- Risks: yield compression in prime, rate sensitivity for mortgage buyers, and speculative off-plan flips.\n- Practical take: Sellers\u2014price to the last 30 days of achieved comps, not Q4 peaks. Buyers\u2014be disciplined, get pre-approved, and don\u2019t overpay for compromised stock.\n\nIf we see two soft months with rising inventory, I\u2019ll call it a broader correction. For now, looks like a healthy reset in parts of the market. #DubaiRealEstate #UAEProperty",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:52:10.162640",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 9,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 8,
                "content": "Useful context: prime is the most volatile slice; a QoQ -8% can happen without a broader crash. The 22% drop in DLD volumes is the bigger signal\u2014financing costs and sentiment are clearly biting.\n\nAs a Dubai mortgage broker, my checklist for clients right now:\n- Stress-test your mortgage at +200 bps on EIBOR; buy only if the payment still fits.\n- Keep LTV conservative; leave room for service charges, insurance, and potential vacancy.\n- Investors: ensure net yield comfortably exceeds your all-in mortgage rate; aim for 1.2x+ interest coverage.\n- On floating rates: ask your bank about caps or switching a portion to fixed; consider small prepayments while rates are elevated.\n- Don\u2019t rely on developer post-handover plans if cash flow is tight\u2014missed payments add up fast.\n\nPrime may soften more, while end-user mid-market can be stickier. Watch USD/UAE rates, supply handovers in H2, and employment/inflows.\n\nHealthy cooling is fine; over-leverage isn\u2019t. #DubaiRealEstate #UAEProperty #MortgageUAE",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:52:34.659440",
                "score": 0
            },
