            {
                "comment_id": 1,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 1,
                "content": "As a first-time buyer saving for a small apartment, this update makes me a bit nervous. Does the 8% QoQ dip in prime spill over into more affordable areas (JVC, IMPZ, Town Square), or is it mostly affecting high-end? With DLD volumes down 22%, are sellers more open to negotiation now, or are listings just pulling back? \n\nAre banks tightening mortgage approvals because of this \"risk-off\" mood? I\u2019m debating whether to lock a fixed rate now or wait 3\u20136 months. Any data on mid-market prices vs rents in Q1 would really help. I don\u2019t want to catch a falling knife, but I\u2019m also worried rents will keep climbing. \n\nFor first-time buyers, what should we be watching most right now\u2014service charges, developer incentives/payment plans, or off-plan risks? Would appreciate insights from agents/analysts.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:43:41.718380",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 2,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 14,
                "content": "Looks like a healthy breather, not a meltdown. I bought a 2BR in Dubai Marina in 2019 and I\u2019m selling now at ~+40%. Good stock is still getting multiple viewings and sensible offers. QoQ \u201cprime\u201d can be super lumpy (seasonality + global jitters), but end-user demand and quality rentals are holding up. If you\u2019re staying long-term: buy quality, great location, solid developer, realistic service charges. Don\u2019t expect 2021\u201323 rocket ships, but A-grade units will be fine. I\u2019m heading back to the UK so I\u2019m cashing out, but if I were staying I\u2019d still be adding in Marina/Downtown/Palm. Doomers shout \u2018top\u2019 every quarter \u2014 it\u2019s usually just a wobble. #DubaiRealEstate",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:46:23.591780",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 3,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 7,
                "content": "Healthy breather, not a breakdown. After record prints, a 20\u201325% volume normalization is textbook in a maturing market. Fundamentals haven\u2019t changed: net migration and company formation (helped by Golden Visas), strong end-user demand, tight rentals, and Vision 2040 driving infrastructure and jobs. \n\nFor end-users and long-term investors, an 8% QoQ dip is a window to lock quality assets\u2014focus on community, build quality, service charges, and cashflow. On our side at Creek Harbour and Dubai Hills, construction is on schedule; we\u2019re rolling out flexible and post-handover plans to de-risk entry. Cycles breathe\u2014opportunity favors the prepared.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:46:30.152960",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 4,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 9,
                "content": "Seen this movie before. QoQ dips after a hot run aren\u2019t a \u201cdownturn\u201d by default. Ramadan/Eid always slow viewings and transfers. Prime sales price \u2260 rental reality \u2014 Marina and JVC viewings are still busy, yields are holding, and collections are >98% on time for me.\n\nSupply coming online is mostly peripheral; true prime stock is tight. Tenants expecting 2020 rents will be disappointed. Renewals are being adjusted within RERA guidelines where units are below market \u2014 that won\u2019t change because of one soft quarter.\n\nHealthy breather > bubble. Watch the next 2 quarters: net migration, new Ejari registrations, vacancy in established towers. If those stay firm, this is consolidation, not a slide. I\u2019m holding my line on rents.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:46:56.802260",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 5,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 10,
                "content": "A cooling in the prime segment doesn\u2019t automatically translate into affordability for ordinary residents. If anything, volume dips can push developers to pause mid-income projects first. This is a window to rebalance supply toward end\u2011users: accelerate approvals for affordable rentals, set inclusionary requirements in large masterplans, release public land for social housing, and incentivize smaller, transit\u2011linked units over trophy assets. Also strengthen tenant protections with predictable rent index updates and discourage land banking.\n\nDubai\u2019s structural demand is still strong (population, jobs, infrastructure), so a sharp downturn isn\u2019t inevitable. It\u2019s a healthy correction only if it reduces speculation and redirects capital to livable, mixed-income communities. Would love to see DLD publish more granular data on prime vs mid-market absorption, vacancy, and rental stress to guide policy. Luxury has its place\u2014but it shouldn\u2019t dominate the pipeline.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:48:10.396400",
                "score": 0
            },
