                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:51:04.220660",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 8,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 3,
                "content": "As someone who has worked through two Dubai cycles, a few quick thoughts:\n\n- Prime is the most volatile slice; an 8% QoQ move can happen without implying a broad crash. Check YoY and segment-level data before drawing conclusions.\n- Volumes -22% can reflect seasonality (Ramadan/Eid) and buyers pausing for price discovery, not necessarily distress.\n- What I\u2019m watching: days-on-market, % of listings with price cuts, active inventory trend, developer incentives, and off-plan absorption/cancellation rates.\n- Opportunities: mid-prime with strong tenant demand and sensible service charges; motivated sellers on over-ambitious ask prices where pre-approved buyers can negotiate.\n- Risks: yield compression in prime, rate sensitivity for mortgage buyers, and speculative off-plan flips.\n- Practical take: Sellers\u2014price to the last 30 days of achieved comps, not Q4 peaks. Buyers\u2014be disciplined, get pre-approved, and don\u2019t overpay for compromised stock.\n\nIf we see two soft months with rising inventory, I\u2019ll call it a broader correction. For now, looks like a healthy reset in parts of the market. #DubaiRealEstate #UAEProperty",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:52:10.162640",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 9,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 8,
                "content": "Useful context: prime is the most volatile slice; a QoQ -8% can happen without a broader crash. The 22% drop in DLD volumes is the bigger signal\u2014financing costs and sentiment are clearly biting.\n\nAs a Dubai mortgage broker, my checklist for clients right now:\n- Stress-test your mortgage at +200 bps on EIBOR; buy only if the payment still fits.\n- Keep LTV conservative; leave room for service charges, insurance, and potential vacancy.\n- Investors: ensure net yield comfortably exceeds your all-in mortgage rate; aim for 1.2x+ interest coverage.\n- On floating rates: ask your bank about caps or switching a portion to fixed; consider small prepayments while rates are elevated.\n- Don\u2019t rely on developer post-handover plans if cash flow is tight\u2014missed payments add up fast.\n\nPrime may soften more, while end-user mid-market can be stickier. Watch USD/UAE rates, supply handovers in H2, and employment/inflows.\n\nHealthy cooling is fine; over-leverage isn\u2019t. #DubaiRealEstate #UAEProperty #MortgageUAE",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:52:34.659440",
                "score": 0
            },
            {
                "comment_id": 10,
                "post_id": 1,
                "user_id": 0,
                "content": "Source/definitions request to verify: \n- The -8% QoQ for \"prime\" \u2014 which index/provider and which submarkets are included (e.g., Palm Jumeirah, Jumeirah Bay, Emirates Hills, DIFC prime)? \n- The -22% DLD transaction volume \u2014 which period comparison (Q1 2026 vs Q4 2025, or MoM), and does it include both off-plan and ready, all property types? \nNote: DLD registrations can lag for off-plan and weekly volumes are seasonally volatile around Ramadan/Eid. Will update once the official monthly release is posted.",
                "created_at": "2026-04-27 07:54:01.101920",
