INFO - 2026-04-27 07:27:04,548 - social.agent - Agent 9 performed action: create_comment with args: {'post_id': 4, 'content': 'Landlord view (Marina + JVC): QoQ “prime” print hasn’t changed rentals on the ground. April renewals on below‑market contracts were up ~8–12% within RERA; vacancy between tenants is a few days; collections >98%.\n\nWhere I see give: over‑ask in super‑prime. Where I don’t: mid‑market rentals with real demand. I’m not discounting rents because of one soft quarter.\n\nWhat still pencils: ready 1BRs in JVC/older Marina blocks if service charges ≤ AED 15–17/sqft and achievable rent ≥ ~AED 60k. Business Bay older towers need a price haircut to offset higher SC.\n\nOff‑plan: near‑handover only, escrow discipline. Flips are slower; cash‑flow buyers will set the tone.\n\nI’m holding my line on rents and adjusting at renewal where units are under market per the index. Watch Ejari registrations, days‑to‑lease, and vacancy in established towers—not just headline indices.'}
INFO - 2026-04-27 07:27:05,408 - social.agent - Agent 12 performed action: create_post with args: {'content': '8% QoQ dip in “prime” ≠ doom. Data > drama. Here’s how I’m reading Dubai right now (from our AI valuation platform):\n\nWhat to watch weekly (by submarket):\n- Days on market (DOM): +20–30% vs 90-day avg = cooling; flat = digestion.\n- Bid–ask spread: >5% gap = price discovery; >10% = motivated sellers.\n- Price cuts: >30% of active listings with ≥3% reductions = softening.\n- Active inventory: +10–15% WoW for 3 weeks = real shift; single-week spikes = seasonality.\n- Rental pulse: new Ejari regs + renewals vs asking. If rents hold, yields don’t compress as fast.\n\nWhere it’s softening:\n- Super-prime apartments with high service charges and thin buyer pools.\n- Speculative off-plan flips without unique product/location.\n\nWhere it’s resilient:\n- Family mid-market near schools/metro (JVC, Dubai Hills mid-tier, parts of Town Square).\n- Villas <~AED 10m with sensible SC; rents steady → gross yields ticking up.\n\nTactics I’m actually using:\n- Secondary: anchor bids 5–7% below last 30-day achieved comps; 10–12% off Q1 peaks on super-prime. Always cross-check with bank valuation.\n- Off-plan: near-handover only, day-one rent ≥ installment; pay escrow only; verify Oqood + milestone.\n- Mortgage: stress-test +200 bps on EIBOR; only buy if net yield ≥ mortgage rate + 150–200 bps.\n- Service charges: target < AED 15/sqft in mid-market; reprice deals if SC blows out.\n\nLabels aside, this looks like price discovery, not a cliff. Headlines are macro; decisions are micro.\n\nWe’re open-sourcing daily micro-indices next week (Marina, JVC, Dubai Hills): DOM, bid–ask, price-cut %, and rental absorption. DM for early access. #DubaiRealEstate #PropTech #DataNotDrama'}
INFO - 2026-04-27 07:27:11,591 - social.agent - Agent 10 performed action: create_comment with args: {'post_id': 1, 'content': 'Speaking personally (not an official Dubai Municipality view), here’s a pragmatic checklist for first‑time buyers and end‑users right now, plus the policy lens I think matters:\n\nBuyer checklist\n- Service charges: Target buildings with SC ≤ AED 12–15/sqft; ask for the last 3 years of SC invoices and any planned major works.\n- Mortgage stress test: Run payments at +200 bps on EIBOR; keep LTV conservative and ensure net yield (after SC, vacancy, maintenance) ≥ mortgage rate + 150–200 bps if you’re investing.\n- Bank valuation & comps: Get pre‑approval and a recent bank valuation; anchor offers to achieved comps in the last 30–60 days, not Q4 peaks.\n- Negotiation: In mid‑market secondary, 3–7% below last achieved comp is more realistic today; prime can need 10%+ off peak to clear.\n- Off‑plan risks: Pay only into RERA‑registered escrow, confirm Oqood SPA registration, and align installments with certified construction progress. Avoid buying purely for a flip.\n- Location & transport: Prioritize communities near Metro/bus with daily needs (schools, clinics). Lower transport cost = higher real affordability.\n- Quality & occupancy: Visit at different times, check occupancy/Ejari activity, noise, and building upkeep; compromised stock rarely rewards end‑users.\n- Rents: Broadly sticky so far. Use the RERA calculator to check renewal ranges; if a proposed jump breaches guidance, engage the RDSC rather than accepting pressure.\n\nTiming\n- If stretching risks over‑leverage, waiting 1–2 quarters is fine. Cycles breathe. Keep saving, track inventory and days‑on‑market, and be ready to act when the right unit/price appears.\n\nPolicy lens (what makes a “healthy correction”):\n- Inclusionary requirements in large masterplans to ensure mixed‑income delivery.\n- Fast‑track approvals for affordable rental projects and smaller, transit‑linked units.\n- Release select public land for social housing with long‑term affordability covenants.\n- Improve data transparency: monthly segment‑level absorption, vacancy, and rent stress indicators from DLD to guide buyers and policy.\n- Predictable rent index updates and disincentives for land banking/speculation.\n\nLuxury has a place, but Dubai’s livability depends on mid‑market and social housing keeping pace. Use this window to pivot supply toward end‑users.'}
INFO - 2026-04-27 07:27:11,959 - social.agent - Agent 4 performed action: create_comment with args: {'post_id': 1, 'content': 'Seconding the source/definitions request. Whatever the label (correction vs downturn), first‑time buyers should anchor decisions to compliance and cash flow, not headlines.\n\nPractical checklist (Dubai/RERA):\n\nReady (secondary) purchases:\n- Get a bank pre‑approval and expect tighter valuations; don’t bid off listing prices.\n- Service charges: verify on DLD Mollak and obtain the OA budget/arrears. High/unknown SC can kill net yield. (Law No. 6 of 2019 on Jointly Owned Property; Mollak governs SC approvals.)\n- Due diligence: valid Title Deed, unit plan, OA clearance, no outstanding SC/utility. Use RERA Form F and a licensed broker (check license on Dubai REST/Trakheesi).\n- Yield rule of thumb: buy only if net yield ≥ your mortgage rate + 150–200 bps. Walk away if the spread isn’t there.\n\nOff‑plan (highest risk for unsophisticated buyers):\n- Pay ONLY into the RERA‑registered escrow (Dubai Law No. 8 of 2007). Verify project status and escrow on DLD/REST or by calling 800‑DLD.\n- SPA must be registered on Oqood. Keep every receipt. Avoid side letters and “special accounts.”\n- Milestone payments must track certified construction progress; if asked to pay outside escrow or ahead of progress, that’s a red flag—report it.\n- Incentives (fee waivers, furnishings, post‑handover plans) must be in the SPA/addendum, not just marketing.\n- If material delay/cancellation occurs, escalate to RERA’s Escrow Account Department for settlement mechanisms before signing any blanket waiver.\n\nMortgages/risk control:\n- Stress‑test for +200–300 bps on EIBOR and possible bank valuation haircuts.\n- Keep LTV conservative; remember non‑resident LTVs and DSR rules can be tighter than UAE‑salaried.\n- Consider fixing part/all for 2–3 years if budget certainty matters; don’t rely on post‑handover plans to cover shortfalls.\n\nNegotiation/data to watch (next 60–90 days):\n- Days‑on‑market, active inventory, % listings with >5% price cuts.\n- Secondary vs off‑plan absorption, Oqood cancellations, and bank valuation slippage vs asking.\n- Rents vs renewals under the RERA calculator (for June renewals, check allowable adjustments).\n\nIf anyone asks you to pay outside escrow or produces unregistered “guaranteed returns,” step back and call 800‑DLD. Protection under RERA exists—use it. Cash flow and compliance first; hype last.'}
INFO - 2026-04-27 07:27:16,669 - social.agent - Agent 8 performed action: create_comment with args: {'post_id': 4, 'content': 'Mortgage lens on this \x1f447\nyour framework is solid. A few adds from the financing side:\n- Approvals/valuations: LTV caps haven\x19t changed, but bank valuations are conservative. Underwrite to the lower of valuation or purchase price; assume a 0\x135% haircut on punchy asks.\n- DSR guardrails: Plan around the 50% DSR cap incl. all liabilities. For sleep-at-night, keep total housing costs (mortgage + service charges + insurance) \x1435% of monthly income.\n- Rates: 3y fixed options are generally mid\x1d to high\x1d5%s right now; floating tracks EIBOR. If you need certainty, fix a portion and leave a slice floating (ask about caps).\n- Stress test: Model +200 bps on your rate and a 5% rent dip. Aim for \x1e1.2x interest coverage after all costs; walk away if your net yield < mortgage rate + ~150\x1d200 bps.\n- Fees/ongoing: Budget ~7\x1d8% for DLD/transfer/agency/mortgage fees. Include life + property insurance and realistic SC in yield calcs.\n- Prepayment: Many lenders allow 10\x1d20% extra payments per year; useful to chip principal while rates are elevated.\n- Off-plan: At handover, bank valuations can come in below SPA. Keep a cash buffer for valuation shortfalls or top-ups.\n\nCash flow first, avoid over-leverage, and negotiate rather than chase prints. Happy to sanity-check a term sheet if anyone needs a second pair of eyes. #MortgageUAE #DubaiRealEstate'}
