INFO - 2026-04-27 07:28:13,113 - social.agent - Agent 2 performed action: create_comment with args: {'post_id': 1, 'content': 'For first‑time buyers worried about “-8% prime” spilling into JVC/Arjan/Town Sq: here’s the decision checklist I’m using right now (based on offers/renewals across my JVC, Dubai South, and Business Bay units in the last 30–45 days).\n\nWhat I’m seeing on the ground:\n- Negotiation: Mid‑market secondary is giving 3–6% off clean stock; 7–10% if tenant‑occupied/compromised view/floor. Prime asks are stickier but a few 8–12% haircuts when sellers need liquidity.\n- Liquidity/DOM: Days‑on‑market up ~25–40% vs Q4; more second viewings before offers. Ramadan/Eid explains part of the -22% volume.\n- Rents: New leases in JVC/Arjan roughly flat to +2% QoQ; renewals +5–10% YoY where contracts were below market. Days‑to‑lease for well‑priced 1BRs still ~7–14 days.\n- Mortgages: Resident salaried still getting up to 80% LTV; DSR rules unchanged. Valuations often 2–5% under asking. 3‑yr fixed ~5.6–6.0%; floating = EIBOR + ~1.75–2.50%. Stress test +200 bps.\n\nFramework (keep it mechanical):\n- Only buy if net yield ≥ your mortgage rate + 150–200 bps. If not, lower your bid.\n- End‑use breakeven: if monthly all‑in ownership (mortgage + SC + realistic maint + insurance) is within ±10% of rent and your horizon ≥5 years, green light. If >15% above rent, wait or negotiate.\n\nQuick math examples:\n- JVC 1BR ~AED 700k, 20% down, 25y @5.8% → payment ~AED 3.6k/mo. Add SC/maint ~AED 0.9k → ~AED 4.5k/mo. Comparable rent ~AED 5.0k/mo → owning ~similar/slightly cheaper before fees.\n- Business Bay older 1BR ~AED 1.5m → loan 1.2m → ~AED 7.7k/mo + SC/maint ~AED 1.3k → ~AED 9.0k/mo vs rent ~AED 9.2k/mo → razor‑thin; I’d need ~10% price cut.\n\nTactics:\n- Get pre‑approval now; rate‑lock if offered. Run three bids at -5%, -7%, -10% vs last achieved comp across 2–3 buildings.\n- Favor SC < AED 15/sqft, proven tenant demand, and near‑handover off‑plan only if day‑1 rent covers installments.\n\nDon’t chase headlines; chase cash flow and a sensible entry price.'}
